---

## ğŸ§ª Methods

### ğŸ“ˆ Centrality Measures

| Measure     | Purpose                           |
| ----------- | --------------------------------- |
| Degree      | Direct connections                |
| Betweenness | Bridge importance                 |
| Closeness   | Average distance to others        |
| Eigenvector | Influence via important neighbors |
| PageRank    | Link-based importance score       |

### ğŸ§© Community Detection

| Algorithm         | Type             | Description                    |
| ----------------- | ---------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Louvain           | Modularity-based | Maximizes modularity           |
| Label Propagation | Diffusion-based  | Neighbor majority labeling     |
| Girvanâ€“Newman     | Divisive         | Removes high-betweenness edges |

---

## ğŸ“Œ Key Findings

* Central nodes are consistently identified across multiple metrics
* Louvain produces well-balanced communities and scales efficiently
* Label Propagation is fast but less stable across runs
* Girvanâ€“Newman provides hierarchical insight but is computationally expensive
* High betweenness nodes often act as bridges between communities

---

## ğŸ§  Conclusion

This project demonstrates how graph mining techniques reveal hidden structures in social networks. By combining centrality analysis with community detection, we gain insights into:

* Influential users
* Community organization
* Algorithm performance trade-offs

